Since my last review, I see the min_ram/min_disk limits are now being checked. 

The exception would not have happened on other databases like SQLite/Oracle but I feel it's okay to cap on MySQL. We may also have a similar issue for BigInt columns like 'size' property if image_size_cap is raised above the signed 8 byte range. But IMO, I don't think we need to address everyone of these considering the practical values that are possible. In short, +1

(1 comment)

Alex, thanks for the review. 

I've answered in the inline comment: this patch is not about checksum validation (we don't need to reinvent the md5 checksum checker here).

Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

Yes, I absolutely agree with Alexey, that this regexp must be here.

The reason of it - we want to compare two different things. We check that input string <=32 symbols, but in db varchar is set to 32 bytes. So, it doesn't matter what string length we have. If we use non-ascii characters there, check in api will pass, but then it will error in db (because we're going to write more than 32 bytes) and 500 response from server.anyway.

Patch Set 11: Mike, there is no need for the regexp to test the invalid checksum string case, as long as the decorator @no_4byte_unicode checks any image param. By the way, I tested the case with invalid characters in the checksum and received valid 400. 400 Bad Request

400 Bad Request

Failed to reserve image. Got error: 400 Bad Request The server could not comply with the request since it is either malformed or otherwise incorrect. Failed to add image metadata. Got error: Checksum can't contain 4 byte unicode characters.
